      <para id="id267453">                            for all <emphasis effect="italics">t</emphasis> in the range of <emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis>.</para>
      <para id="id267478">We have a tie to the simple case of conditioning with respect to an event. If
<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>C</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>{</m:mo><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo>∈</m:mo><m:mi>M</m:mi><m:mo>}</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> has positive probability, then using <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mi>C</m:mi></m:msub><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mi>M</m:mi></m:msub><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> we have</para>
      <equation id="id267537">
        <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mrow>
