      <para id="id267641">Two properties of expectation are crucial here:</para>
      <list id="id267648" display="block" list-type="enumerated"><item id="uid11">By the uniqueness property <link document="m23998" target-id="uid9">(E5)</link>, since (A) holds for all reasonable (Borel) sets, then <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> is
unique a.s. (i.e., except for a set of <emphasis effect="italics">ω</emphasis> of probability zero).
</item>
        <item id="uid12">By the special case of the Radon Nikodym theorem <link document="m23998" target-id="uid34">(E19)</link>, the function <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math><emphasis effect="italics">always
exists</emphasis> and is such that random variable <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> is unique a.s.
</item>
      </list>
      <para id="id267742">We make a definition based on these facts.</para>
      <para id="id267746"><emphasis effect="bold">Definition</emphasis>.  The <emphasis effect="italics">conditional expectation</emphasis><m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mo>[</m:mo><m:mi>g</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>Y</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo><m:mo>|</m:mo><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>t</m:mi><m:mo>]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>e</m:mi><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>t</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> is the a.s. unique
function defined on the range of <emphasis effect="italics">X</emphasis> such that</para>
      <equation id="id267810">
        <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mo>(</m:mo>
              <m:mi>A</m:mi>
              <m:mo>)</m:mo>
            </m:mrow>
